\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def maxStrength(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        if len(nums) == 1:\n            return nums[0]\n        \n        positive_nums = [num for num in nums if num > 0]\n        negative_nums = [num for num in nums if num < 0]\n        \n        # If there are no positive numbers and at most one negative number, we must pick the largest (least negative) number\n        if not positive_nums and len(negative_nums) <= 1:\n            return max(nums)\n        \n        # Sort negative numbers to pick the largest (least negative) ones\n        negative_nums.sort()\n        \n        # If the number of negative numbers is odd, we can only take the largest even count of them\n        if len(negative_nums) % 2 != 0:\n            negative_nums.pop()  # Remove the smallest (most negative) number\n        \n        max_strength = 1\n        for num in positive_nums + negative_nums:\n            max_strength *= num\n        \n        return max_strength\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- We separate the positive and negative numbers from the input list.\n- If there are no positive numbers and at most one negative number, the maximum strength is the largest number in the list (which could be negative).\n- We sort the negative numbers to easily pick the least negative ones.\n- If the count of negative numbers is odd, we discard the smallest (most negative) number to make the product positive.\n- We multiply all the selected positive and negative numbers to get the maximum strength.\n- This approach ensures that we maximize the product by considering the optimal combination of positive and negative numbers.", "estimated_date": 1684627200000}